🔗 What is Coupling?

Coupling = how strongly two classes depend on each other

If one class change → affects another → high coupling (bad)
If classes are independent → low coupling (good)
🔴 Tight Coupling (Bad Design)

👉 One class is directly dependent on another class

Example:
class Engine {
    void start() {
        System.out.println("Engine started");
    }
}

class Car {
    Engine e = new Engine();   // tightly coupled

    void drive() {
        e.start();
        System.out.println("Car is driving");
    }
}
❌ Problem Here
Car is directly tied to Engine
If you change Engine → Car breaks
Cannot reuse Car easily

👉 No flexibility

🟢 Loose Coupling (Good Design)

👉 We reduce dependency using abstraction (interface or abstract class)

Example Using Interface
interface Engine {
    void start();
}
class PetrolEngine implements Engine {
    public void start() {
        System.out.println("Petrol Engine started");
    }
}
class ElectricEngine implements Engine {
    public void start() {
        System.out.println("Electric Engine started");
    }
}
Car Class (Now Flexible)
class Car {
    Engine e;

    Car(Engine e) {   // dependency injection
        this.e = e;
    }

    void drive() {
        e.start();
        System.out.println("Car is driving");
    }
}
Usage
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Engine e = new ElectricEngine();
        Car c = new Car(e);

        c.drive();
    }
}
💥 Why This is Powerful

Now you can switch engines easily:

Engine e = new PetrolEngine();   // change here only

👉 Car doesn’t care what engine it gets

🧠 Core Difference
Tight Coupling	Loose Coupling
Direct dependency	Uses abstraction
Hard to change	Easy to change
Less reusable	More reusable
Rigid design	Flexible design
🔥 Real Interview Line (Remember This)

👉 “Loose coupling is achieved using abstraction and dependency injection